            "currentCldrName": "See-No-Evil Monkey",
            "description": "<p>The <i>see no evil</i> <em>monkey</em>, called <i>Mizaru </i>(Japanese for &ldquo;see not&rdquo;), one of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three_wise_monkeys\">Three Wise Monkeys</a>. Depicted as the brown <a href=\"/monkey-face/\">üêµ Monkey Face</a> with hands covering its eyes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Three Wise Monkeys represent the proverb <i>see no evil, hear no evil, speak no evil</i>, frequently interpreted as&nbsp;a call for discretion or willful ignorance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Often used as a playful way to convey a laughing, disbelieving, cringing&nbsp;<em>I can&rsquo;t believe what I&rsquo;m seeing!</em> or <i>I can&rsquo;t bear to look!</i></p>\r\n\r\n<p>See also <a href=\"/hear-no-evil-monkey/\">üôâ Hear-No-Evil Monkey</a> and <a href=\"/speak-no-evil-monkey/\">üôä Speak-No-Evil Monkey</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This emoji is considered <a href=\"https://blog.emojipedia.org/how-the-monkey-emoji-is-racist/\">racist in some contexts</a>, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people.</p>",
